{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510966"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11667"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11667"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.4,0.08,0.27,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4288"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115063"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4288"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26968"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115063"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the general practice with his wife, who reported that during the past year, her husband has started to show personality changes, including increased irritability and these have been steadily worsening. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has also started to suffer problems in doing his work as accountant. She has also noticed purposeless, irregular, jerking movements that involve his face, limbs and trunk. He denies involuntary movement, but admits to having recently fallen down a flight of stairs. He has no siblings and his father, who was institutionalised, committed suicide at age of 40 years. An MRI brain is done (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to be abnormal?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thalamus","Caudate nucleus","Cerebellum","Substantia nigra","Subthalamic nucleus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u2019s presentation with abnormal movement, personality changes, and cognitive decline suggests Huntington\u2019s disease (HD). The MRI brain shows a dilated lateral ventricle. HD is an autosomal dominant neurodegenerative condition with the usual age of onset between 30 and 50 years. It characterised by a progressive, usually choreiform movement disorder, dementia, and psychiatric disturbances, ultimately leading to death. The pathologic hallmark of Huntington\u2019s disease is progressive atrophy of the striatum, especially involving the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaudate nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E. Atrophy of the caudate head causes the adjacent lateral ventricles to appear enlarged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA lesion in the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethalamus\u003C/strong\u003E produces a variety of manifestations, according to the exact site of lesions, including sensory deficit, thalamic pain syndrome, amnesia, choreoathetosis, and hallucination. The patient\u2019s presentation and family history is more suggestive of Huntington\u2019s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA lesion in \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum \u003C/strong\u003Eproduces intention tremors, slurred or scanning speech, rebound phenomenon, hypotonia, and ataxic gait.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELesions in\u003Cstrong\u003E substantia nigra\u003C/strong\u003E manifest as resting tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia. This is commonly seen in Parkinson disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELesions in the \u003Cstrong\u003Esubthalamic nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E manifest as hemiballismus, which is large-amplitude movements that are jerking or flailing in appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HD is caused by an autosomal dominantly inherited CAG trinucleotide repeat expansion in the huntingtin (HTT) gene on chromosome 4.","HD is characterised by cognitive (impaired emotion recognition, processing speed, visuospatial and executive function), motor (chorea, dystonia, balance and gait disturbance) and neuropsychiatric disturbance (apathy, anxiety, irritability, depression, obsessive compulsive behaviour and psychosis).","in HD atrophy of caudate nucleus causes enlargement of the frontal horns of the lateral ventricles"],"references":["Andhale R, Shrivastava D. Huntington\u0027s Disease: A Clinical Review. Cureus. 2022 Aug 27;14(8):e28484. doi: 10.7759/cureus.28484. PMID: 36176885; PMCID: PMC9512951. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36176885/","Image: Frank Gaillard, CC BY-SA 3.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons","Jimenez-Sanchez M, Licitra F, Underwood BR, Rubinsztein DC. Huntington\u0027s Disease: Mechanisms of Pathogenesis and Therapeutic Strategies. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2017 Jul 5;7(7):a024240. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a024240. PMID: 27940602; PMCID: PMC5495055. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5495055/","Ajitkumar A, De Jesus O. Huntington Disease. [Updated 2023 Aug 23]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559166/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11667"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17824"}]},